          Before we get into the drastic measures for reducing your CSS size and increasing performance, 
          let's take a quick look at what you should be doing already. 
        

        h3 Specificity
        p.
          What's great about this advice is that it's appropriate whether you're using vanilla CSS
          or something tastier like SASS. (God forbid you're using a post-processor. Are there meta CSS pre-processors yet?)
          Let's have a look-see at the first culprit:
        

        p
          code.
            .table tr > td .data {
              color:#fffffe;
            }
				
        p.
          Seriously? This is awful. A great analogy for this is one's family tree. We don't often say
          "my brother's kid", do we? No. We say "my nephew". See, in every facet of life we try to 
          minimize specificity!

        p.
          If we look to the selector above we can ask ourselves an (!)important question: does the element
          with the <code>.data</code> class <em>really</em> appear somewhere else within a 
          <code>.table</code>? If not, why are you trying to find one's only within a <code>td</code> element 
          that is a direct child of a <code>tr</code> (which is also a problem in itself)?

